  "texts": [
    "In view of Proposition 3.2.10 the law of composition of morphisms is satisfied.",
    "Functors κ[I, ⋅] (Knit) and ca[I] (Canon)There is a functorκ ≡ κ[I, ⋅] ∶ bpol • [I, ⋅] → P 2 ⊂ [I]defined by the association a → κ a and for a BG-map f ∶ a → b, κ(f) is the inclusion κ a ↪ κ b.",
    "It is easy to verify the functor axioms by relying on Proposition 3.2.10 and Proposition 3.2.6.P 2 ⊂ [I] bpol • [I, ⋅] ca κ κ a κ b a b i κa κ b f X Y ca(X) ca(Y) i X Y i X Y (15)On the opposite direction we define a functor ca ≡ ca[I] ∶ P 2 ⊂ (I) → bpol • [I, ⋅] by associating to any object X ∈ P 2 (I) the canonical p-site associated to X, namely ca(X) ∶= ca(I, X) (Definition 1.5.4), and to any morphism iX Y we put ca(i X Y) ∶= i X Y.",
    "Indeed if i X Y is a morphism of P 2 ⊂ (I) one has π ca(X) = id X = id Y ○ i X Y = π ca(Y) ○ i X Y.",
    "It follows, in view of Proposition 3.1.3, that the inclusion i XY is a BG-map between ca(X) and ca(Y)."
